******
[2]
Date: Sat 6 Jul 2013
Source: Omaha.com [edited]
http://www.omaha.com/article/20130706/LIVEWELL01/707069927#nebraska-iowa-report-14-more-cases-of-nasty-bug-that-causes-diarrhea


14 more cases of cyclosporiasis were reported Friday [5 Jul 2013] in Nebraska and Iowa, adding to the 12 that had come in over the past several days.

Officials still are trying to determine the source of the _Cyclospora cayetanensis_ parasite, which causes an intestinal infection called cyclosporiasis. They're telling physicians to be aware of the illness and to test specifically for the parasite.

_Cyclospora cayetanensis_ is a parasite made of one cell, too small to be seen without a microscope. Cyclospora parasites are spread by people ingesting something, such as food or water, that is contaminated with feces. Cyclospora needs days to weeks after being passed in a bowel movement to become infectious for another person. Therefore, it is unlikely that cyclospora is passed directly from one person to another.

[Byline: Bob Glissmann]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Infection with _Cyclospora cayetansis_ is usually due to contaminated berries and may be waterborne. The multi-location outbreak reported here strongly suggests that it is due to contaminated fruits of some kind distributed to retailers over a large area.

The epidemiology has recently been reviewed (Chacin-Bonilla L: Epidemiology of _Cyclospora cayetanensis_: A review focusing in endemic areas. Acta Trop. 2010; 115(3): 181-93; available at http://ipac.kacst.edu.sa/eDoc/2010/190711_1.pdf. Ortega YR, Sanchez R: Update on _Cyclospora cayetanensis_, a food-borne and waterborne parasite. Clin Microbiol Rev. 2010; 23(1): 218-34; available at http://cmr.asm.org/cgi/content/full/23/1/218). More information on Cyclospora can be found at: http://www.cdc.gov/parasites/cyclosporiasis/.

HealthMap/ProMED-mail maps for Iowa and Nebraska can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/3mqs and http://healthmap.org/r/2NN9.
- Mod.EP]
